WEBVTT

00:00.898 --> 00:03.861
Hey everybody, welcome to the Menlo Midweek Podcast.

00:03.901 --> 00:05.343
We are so glad you could join us today.

00:05.683 --> 00:06.364
My name is Matt.

00:06.725 --> 00:07.225
And I'm Phil.

00:07.646 --> 00:16.255
And I am not Mark Mornishi, our previous host, but that's okay because Mark is on to more amazing things, but we're still diving in into the podcast today.

00:16.315 --> 00:20.700
So if you're just joining us for the first time ever, we talk about a bunch of different things here.

00:20.901 --> 00:29.330
Mostly we talk about what our church is talking about, big conversations at our messages or our sermons, but sometimes we dive into some other fun topics.

00:29.506 --> 00:35.612
Last Sunday, Phil, we jumped into a new series titled, I Am The God Who Gets Close.

00:35.732 --> 00:48.665
And so I just want to ask you, Phil, if someone's listening who's never really given church much thought, or maybe they've assumed God is distant or disappointed, what's one thing from this message that you'd want them to lean in and consider?

00:49.526 --> 00:57.714
I think that oftentimes the way we think about church today and oftentimes the thing that becomes most off-putting for people who are not in church is that

00:58.082 --> 00:59.103
I have to be perfect.

00:59.323 --> 01:00.825
I have to have it all put together.

01:01.225 --> 01:13.199
And not just the conversation that we had this last weekend with Moses, but over and over and over again, the universal principle in the Bible is that the people that God chooses to get close to are sinful.

01:13.399 --> 01:14.019
They're broken.

01:14.039 --> 01:14.820
They make mistakes.

01:15.581 --> 01:23.730
And the great news of hope that God makes available to us is that that is basically the assumed baseline situation

01:23.810 --> 01:25.694
of all people for God to love us."

01:26.095 --> 01:27.678
So you're like, well, God only loves perfect people.

01:27.778 --> 01:30.624
Actually, God does not love any perfect people because none of those people exist.

01:31.044 --> 01:32.367
He only loves broken people.

01:32.808 --> 01:38.098
And so the more broken you are, hopefully that maybe just piques your interest to go, could that really be true?

01:38.840 --> 01:43.950
And what we say is that the hope of heaven and the love of God for you is honestly too good not to be true.

01:44.030 --> 01:46.034
Like I think our hearts call out to it.

01:46.370 --> 01:51.817
It's a beautiful sentiment and something that I hope resonates with anyone, wherever they are in the spectrum of spirituality.

01:51.837 --> 01:55.361
So this Sunday, we focus in on the story of Moses.

01:56.122 --> 01:58.926
Now, if you haven't read scripture before, it's a pretty big one.

01:59.547 --> 02:08.658
But if you've never seen the movie, The Prince of Egypt, go rethink your life choices because it is one of the most celebrated animated vignettes around

02:08.706 --> 02:13.052
uh, one of the most notable stories within scripture that's so profound and so important.

02:13.112 --> 02:15.395
So, um, so you have homework from this podcast.

02:15.435 --> 02:16.837
It is go, go and watch that.

02:17.098 --> 02:18.259
Go watch an animated film.

02:18.480 --> 02:18.720
Yes.

02:18.780 --> 02:19.621
Go watch an animated film.

02:19.661 --> 02:21.564
That seems like an easy lift, but you can do it.

02:21.704 --> 02:22.125
Yeah.

02:22.145 --> 02:22.726
Yeah.

02:22.746 --> 02:24.328
But it's, I mean, fantastic movie.

02:24.368 --> 02:25.129
I saw it in theaters.

02:25.530 --> 02:29.635
Um, I'm pretty sure my mom started praying halfway through the movie because she thought it was so good.

02:29.675 --> 02:31.458
But anyway, um, great story.

02:31.478 --> 02:37.266
So, I mean, you mentioned in that, um, you said this line that God didn't speak.

02:37.794 --> 02:39.637
until Moses stopped.

02:40.057 --> 02:45.165
This is Moses, I think, connecting with that burning bush, that profound image right there.

02:45.306 --> 02:52.316
And so I would just say, in 2026, we have AI assistants, we have optimized calendars, we have noise everywhere.

02:52.817 --> 02:55.501
What does turning aside practically look like?

02:56.042 --> 03:06.418
Yeah, I think that if you don't live in Silicon Valley, this may be something you will pretty quickly see us true, but don't live with as much as those of us who are in Silicon Valley live with.

03:06.690 --> 03:10.034
which is we are in the attention economy, like we are.

03:10.834 --> 03:15.399
And what I give my attention to, I will eventually give my affection to.

03:15.459 --> 03:16.701
And God knows that too.

03:17.341 --> 03:25.210
And I think that there are so many different things that are beeping and buzzing and clamoring for our attention.

03:25.610 --> 03:29.535
And I don't think that God wants to be one of those beeping and buzzing.

03:29.735 --> 03:32.818
And you know, like, I think that the burning bush is about as,

03:33.090 --> 03:34.432
you know, bright as it's going to get.

03:34.492 --> 03:41.301
And even that, as I mentioned this weekend, was kind of subtle, like seeing a bush like that wasn't new, seeing one of them on fire probably wasn't new.

03:41.401 --> 03:45.386
It was like this double take of like, wait a second, that one's not burning up.

03:45.727 --> 03:56.822
And I think that for our relationship and conversation with God, he is usually trying to get our attention first because he wants our affection.

03:57.523 --> 04:02.930
But I think that oftentimes he's going to function at the pace at which we are willing

04:03.074 --> 04:05.737
to listen that we are willing to pay attention.

04:05.877 --> 04:11.102
Now, I will say if you're a follower of Jesus, I think that's often true for someone that's not a follower of Jesus.

04:11.522 --> 04:17.829
I think if you're a follower of Jesus, what the Bible says is that those the Lord loves He corrects like a loving parent.

04:17.969 --> 04:21.112
And so I think God starts with subtlety.

04:22.033 --> 04:31.442
And then I think if you're a follower of Jesus, and especially if you're living in active disobedience to the way of Jesus, it may feel really frustrating in the moment,

04:31.778 --> 04:35.604
but it's actually out of love that he's gonna bring correction to you.

04:35.664 --> 04:54.494
So I think it's a little bit, there's some subtlety in it, but I do think it's important to recognize all the things in our life that are trying to get our attention, trying to get our attention, trying to get our attention, all the ways that we're multitasking, they're having a deforming impact on our ability to focus on anything, certainly including God.

04:54.514 --> 04:57.298
And I would just hope that if you're here on this,

04:57.442 --> 05:01.811
just recognize that we are being formed and shaped every single moment by different things.

05:02.392 --> 05:06.821
There is a formational force that exists in our world upon our souls.

05:07.422 --> 05:09.506
And so I resonate with that deeply.

05:09.647 --> 05:13.394
And I think too, I am so overwhelmed and distracted.

05:13.666 --> 05:18.636
God would have to set my car on fire for me, for me to know that like, Oh, I think something's wrong.

05:18.696 --> 05:20.139
Maybe I should pay attention.

05:20.460 --> 05:23.446
And if it was the Honda, I'm sure that would even wear it.

05:23.466 --> 05:25.771
Honestly, it might be a gift.

05:26.292 --> 05:28.236
Oh God, thank you so much for setting this.

05:28.256 --> 05:30.501
2008 Honda on fire.

05:31.282 --> 05:32.385
I wondered what to do with it.

05:32.405 --> 05:34.930
Although it would be, it would be a problem if it never went out.

05:35.170 --> 05:39.495
Yeah, that I mean, well, and honestly with hybrid batteries, it might not.

05:39.876 --> 05:40.536
Yeah, yeah, absolutely.

05:40.556 --> 05:41.658
It might be a bigger problem.

05:42.539 --> 05:49.768
But yeah, I think God finds really creative ways to get our attention and what we do with that matters so much.

05:49.868 --> 05:52.851
How is it landing on us and what is it catalyzing within us?

05:52.971 --> 05:58.778
And Moses, I don't think he was a young man when he experienced that moment.

05:58.798 --> 06:00.881
It was something that was kind of far on for him.

06:01.301 --> 06:02.923
And I think there's something there.

06:02.963 --> 06:05.106
Moses had

06:05.506 --> 06:09.151
He just had a pretty robust life up to that point.

06:09.331 --> 06:15.059
And I think when I'm thinking about now is just kind of his age and status and experience.

06:15.139 --> 06:26.835
And so like, what are we supposed to do when we feel like we've arrived or further along in life and we encounter something that can radically change and or disorient us at our age and stage?

06:26.915 --> 06:27.976
How do we reconcile?

06:28.377 --> 06:29.298
Well, no, I've arrived.

06:29.338 --> 06:30.099
I've made it already.

06:31.621 --> 06:35.186
How are we supposed to hear God in that when maybe we're so entrenched?

06:35.426 --> 06:37.489
in our own trajectory.

06:37.989 --> 06:46.800
Yeah, I think a lot of the markers that we have for what success looks like in 2026 prioritize wealth over wisdom.

06:48.162 --> 06:48.302
Yeah.

06:48.422 --> 06:58.735
And I think that for the most part, when we look at the trajectory in scripture, certainly if you go look at proverbs, but I think it's more broadly applicable wider than that.

06:59.536 --> 07:04.082
The scripture actually values wisdom over wealth.

07:05.122 --> 07:09.087
And so I think some of it is moving the north star of what we define as success.

07:09.908 --> 07:15.155
If we define wealth as success, I think part of the challenge is that wealth is relative.

07:15.875 --> 07:23.865
So it's always funny when you read the surveys about people at different income levels when you say, Hey, what number would you need to make to feel rich?

07:24.626 --> 07:29.793
And every person puts a number bigger than what they have that the goalposts just keep moving.

07:30.654 --> 07:33.938
And then there's a group of people that I think they would say,

07:34.594 --> 07:35.275
Uh, you know what?

07:35.295 --> 07:35.976
I have arrived.

07:36.957 --> 07:38.259
My startup got acquired.

07:38.299 --> 07:39.341
We went public.

07:40.382 --> 07:44.869
I mean, there are people in the valley that they have more money than they could spend in multiple lifetimes.

07:45.910 --> 07:50.156
And I think that's like the dog that caught the car moment of they're chasing it.

07:50.176 --> 07:50.717
They're chasing it.

07:50.737 --> 07:52.059
They're chasing is instinctive.

07:52.539 --> 07:55.944
They catch it and they're going like, Oh, now what?

07:55.964 --> 08:02.834
And I think that wealth is oftentimes when, especially when wealth is disconnected from wisdom,

08:03.106 --> 08:04.648
Wealth becomes very consuming.

08:05.409 --> 08:06.230
What do I consume?

08:06.250 --> 08:07.232
What do I get out of it?

08:07.672 --> 08:12.439
When it's applied with wisdom or when we have wisdom, maybe even without wealth, it becomes generative.

08:12.659 --> 08:13.761
It can help other people.

08:13.881 --> 08:15.423
It can be a blessing and a benefit.

08:15.964 --> 08:29.362
And when I build my life with a north start of wisdom, I think there's this beautiful expression where, you know, I've talked about this a lot lately that I think we've never been at a time where information is more readily available.

08:29.698 --> 08:32.302
Information is just content, right?

08:32.342 --> 08:36.688
And we have more content being created in any moment than at every moment ever.

08:36.708 --> 08:44.799
It's why all these, you know, crazy technology things are happening all around us, but that knowledge, which is true information, that takes curation.

08:44.819 --> 08:46.141
It takes us figuring it out.

08:46.161 --> 08:48.544
You can't just take all information at face value.

08:49.285 --> 08:53.951
And then underneath that is wisdom, which is knowledge applied in real life.

08:53.991 --> 08:58.738
So information, wisdom, or information, knowledge, wisdom, I think wisdom's never been more rare.

08:59.106 --> 09:06.097
And wisdom is one of those things that I think if we prioritize it in our life, we get better with age, right?

09:06.137 --> 09:07.759
Like actually like a fine wine.

09:08.240 --> 09:15.731
You can sit down with someone who is 20 something years old with a teenager and you're in your 70s and you're in your 80s.

09:15.771 --> 09:18.255
And by the grace of God, you're going, you know what?

09:18.636 --> 09:21.881
Let me tell you that story about the time that I walked through something like what you're walking through.

09:21.901 --> 09:23.623
Yeah, circumstances were different.

09:24.044 --> 09:26.568
We didn't have, you know, cars that drove themselves yet.

09:26.788 --> 09:28.050
You know, I was driving stick.

09:28.162 --> 09:34.710
Yeah, I lived in a different part of the country, but wisdom is wisdom because wisdom is just knowledge applied.

09:35.150 --> 09:44.622
So I think a core to it for me is how do I make sure in my own life and in my own spiritual formation that wisdom is the leading marker of my spiritual maturity.

09:44.962 --> 09:51.009
And I don't allow wealth and the deformative nature of success in the Valley and in the Western culture in general.

09:51.310 --> 09:51.710
Take shape.

09:51.871 --> 09:52.591
Yeah, that's great.

09:52.651 --> 09:55.775
I mean, wealth influence power, all of those things.

09:56.796 --> 09:58.098
They exist in every

09:58.210 --> 10:01.753
paradigm around us just at different scales.

10:02.214 --> 10:07.639
So if you're listening and you're like, oh, I knew there was artificial intelligence, just be reassured there is no artificial wisdom.

10:07.779 --> 10:08.760
Like that doesn't happen.

10:09.922 --> 10:11.643
Yeah, we need to have the pain.

10:11.843 --> 10:21.813
And I mean, if you think about what AI is doing, even if you were to ask AI for wisdom, all it's doing, and I mean, we've talked about this before, all AI is doing in any expression of it right now.

10:21.993 --> 10:23.114
It's a large language model.

10:23.195 --> 10:24.055
It's machine learning.

10:24.576 --> 10:26.738
It's taking a whole bunch of stuff that's been

10:26.946 --> 10:33.552
put inside of it as its sort of sample source, and it's giving you a predictive answer based on probability.

10:34.153 --> 10:44.763
So it may have a photocopy of a photocopy of a photocopy, but it has never had to live out the lessons of information curated to knowledge applied in life.

10:45.524 --> 10:51.309
And I think that's one of those areas that as image bearers of the creator of the universe, that makes us distinct.

10:51.790 --> 10:56.274
When I share wisdom with someone, that's wisdom that I've learned the hard way.

10:56.642 --> 11:02.070
I didn't read 7,000 books and I'm giving you the average of those 7,000 books.

11:02.330 --> 11:04.434
That's what a chatbot is giving you.

11:04.454 --> 11:04.554
Yeah.

11:05.215 --> 11:08.239
So yeah, it's way more informative than it is experiential.

11:08.800 --> 11:22.520
And the, the, the human wiring imparted by God into us of, of emotion and, and grief and gladness and goodness, like all those things that we carry, like there's no artificial expression of that.

11:22.580 --> 11:26.386
And I think that the, you know, you talked about the influence nature

11:26.946 --> 11:46.133
I think that influencer culture too has distorted wisdom a little bit where I think about like the Manosphere stuff where you have these guys that are like, oh, we'll tell you how to be this amazing, you know, very attractive, very successful individual.

11:46.193 --> 11:48.456
And they purport wisdom.

11:48.477 --> 11:50.840
And I think people are so hungry for wisdom.

11:50.900 --> 11:54.545
They'll take fake wisdom as long as it's said confidently.

11:54.565 --> 11:55.186
Yeah.

11:55.266 --> 12:00.011
And then you come out and you realize like, oh, Andrew Tate is like, turns out, not a great guy, you know?

12:00.051 --> 12:01.593
Like, oh, that's awful.

12:02.093 --> 12:05.277
And I think wisdom is best shared in relationship.

12:05.297 --> 12:09.541
And so this idea of like, well, how do I get a platform and how do I have even more people listen to me?

12:09.561 --> 12:13.705
And I mean, that's ironic for me to say because we're talking into microphones that's going on podcast.

12:13.745 --> 12:17.389
But I would say like the best wisdom that I give is with my kids.

12:17.970 --> 12:19.091
It's like face to face.

12:19.211 --> 12:21.173
It's time with them because they know me.

12:21.213 --> 12:21.874
They know.

12:21.986 --> 12:30.097
If the person that they're hearing on stage or that they hear in a recording is the same person that walks into the house or not, are we consistent people?

12:30.157 --> 12:37.587
And when we have consistent people in our life and they share wisdom with us, I think we should significantly prioritize that wisdom in the way we live our lives.

12:37.667 --> 12:38.428
Yeah, that's great.

12:38.568 --> 12:41.812
And there is a hunger for wisdom out there.

12:42.133 --> 12:46.078
And I see it showing up in unusual places.

12:46.238 --> 12:51.986
And a lot of the stuff that's out there, like the hunger analogy sticks with me, like, I think we are settling.

12:52.450 --> 12:57.397
for just like cat food when we could be having like a full meal in the process.

12:57.437 --> 12:59.299
But it takes times, you have to cook it, you know?

12:59.340 --> 13:00.461
Like it's not gonna be ready made.

13:00.481 --> 13:01.422
Like you gotta go through that.

13:01.823 --> 13:02.804
So that just resonates with it.

13:02.824 --> 13:15.702
Well, I think that's a great metaphor because how often do you let yourself get so hungry that you're willing to settle because you haven't actually done it when you anticipate the need for the food, right?

13:16.143 --> 13:19.487
So the right time for wisdom is actually before you need it.

13:19.868 --> 13:21.330
It's to be able to go, hey, I've,

13:21.602 --> 13:23.004
a college decision coming up.

13:23.124 --> 13:23.605
Oh, you know what?

13:23.665 --> 13:31.538
I'm sensing some things in my workplace that there is something confusing about what's being asked of me here.

13:31.878 --> 13:35.845
I see these changes coming in the world of my industry.

13:35.865 --> 13:37.027
I want to talk to somebody about that.

13:37.067 --> 13:38.629
Our family's going through a big milestone.

13:39.010 --> 13:43.918
Let me go find somebody that I know that I have close relationship with and just ask for their counsel.

13:43.978 --> 13:45.160
Ask for them to pray with me.

13:45.600 --> 13:49.106
Ask that they would share with me what God has taught them in this season.

13:49.218 --> 13:59.450
when we don't do that and we get to the panic moment, that's when we're looking for like the wisdom, microwavable burrito that we would have never thought about one time before.

13:59.890 --> 14:02.393
But now we're just like, I'm starving, like I have to do something.

14:02.693 --> 14:04.755
And this is what's most dangerous for me.

14:05.016 --> 14:06.878
I don't know if you do this.

14:06.898 --> 14:12.044
I get to a point in the day where I know it's like kind of too late for me to eat lunch.

14:12.805 --> 14:17.650
And I know like if I eat lunch, I won't be hungry for dinner and then I'm gonna have a problem in my marriage.

14:17.858 --> 14:21.942
And so if I let it go too long, I actually don't eat.

14:22.903 --> 14:28.690
And I wonder in our own pursuit of wisdom, if there are these moments where it's like, well, I've actually waited too long.

14:28.750 --> 14:30.812
I don't really know where to get information.

14:30.832 --> 14:32.774
So I'm just going to hit the easy button.

14:32.854 --> 14:33.975
I'm going to do my instinct.

14:34.135 --> 14:40.182
I'm going to ask a technological tool to outsource my brain development or my spiritual formation.

14:40.222 --> 14:42.124
And I'll just get to the next thing.

14:42.224 --> 14:43.986
So I do think that idea

14:44.130 --> 14:50.457
How do we anticipate what we need and make space for relationship and wisdom before the information's mission critical?

14:50.797 --> 14:51.658
Yeah, that's great.

14:52.278 --> 15:00.647
And I think too, you mentioned in the message that you had a section about the desert trying to rename us, failure, divorce, burnout.

15:00.867 --> 15:07.554
And I think like that the desert can be a diagnostic for how we need wisdom.

15:08.055 --> 15:11.058
And so I would just say like, what are you seeing right now?

15:11.330 --> 15:15.335
That is a desert name that people are carrying like how are you?

15:15.715 --> 15:16.516
What are you experiencing?

15:16.536 --> 15:17.337
Who are you talking to?

15:17.417 --> 15:18.399
How you feeling that right now?

15:18.519 --> 15:33.016
Yeah, I think that we're watching a level of disruption that we've never seen in my lifetime That when someone asks especially someone asks you professionally hey, what do you do for?

15:33.036 --> 15:41.106
I mean the history of the world certainly in the post-industrial revolution era the answer to that question

15:41.602 --> 15:43.124
What you're answering is who am I?

15:43.785 --> 15:44.205
What do you do?

15:44.706 --> 15:45.687
What you're answering is who am I?

15:46.388 --> 15:47.270
It shouldn't be that way.

15:47.290 --> 15:49.573
That actually shouldn't be your identity, but we settled for it.

15:50.113 --> 15:50.854
I'm a sales guy.

15:50.894 --> 15:51.736
I'm an executive.

15:51.836 --> 15:52.737
I'm an electrician.

15:52.917 --> 15:53.638
I'm a homemaker.

15:53.698 --> 15:55.621
I'm like, whatever you're answering, I'm a professor.

15:56.222 --> 15:57.643
You're answering identity.

15:58.324 --> 16:04.352
And so in the world of like, well, what happens if your job, what happens if your industry radically changes or goes away?

16:05.334 --> 16:05.794
Well, what is that?

16:06.055 --> 16:11.602
If my job is my identity and this thing is going to take away my job, does that take away my identity?

16:12.066 --> 16:20.659
And so I think that idea of a false identity being exposed, I think that's really big right now.

16:21.500 --> 16:28.090
And to be able to recognize what does it look like to aim higher?

16:28.110 --> 16:32.096
We've talked about this before, but we all have an identity.

16:32.256 --> 16:33.738
At Menlo, we talk about this a lot.

16:33.838 --> 16:38.766
Our mission at Menlo is bringing hope to everyone by living out our identity in Christ every day.

16:38.826 --> 16:41.810
You're a love child of God.

16:41.922 --> 16:48.088
created in his image with infinite dignity, value, and worth broken for sure in need of healing, hope, and heaven, absolutely.

16:48.769 --> 16:50.651
But those things can't be taken away from you.

16:50.691 --> 16:52.593
That's primary.

16:52.693 --> 16:55.095
And then from there, we have our calling.

16:55.195 --> 16:57.778
Our calling is usually wrapped up in our gifts and our abilities.

16:58.238 --> 16:59.059
And so what is that?

16:59.279 --> 17:01.541
Have you spent time identifying that?

17:01.561 --> 17:10.290
For me, if I wasn't at Menlo, I would be working to hopefully bring health and healing

17:10.850 --> 17:12.692
to a community of faith of some kind.

17:12.773 --> 17:14.235
Like that is actually my calling.

17:14.996 --> 17:18.200
And then within my calling is my assignment.

17:18.700 --> 17:21.985
And my assignment right now is the lead pastor of Menlo Church.

17:22.005 --> 17:24.008
And by God's grace, it will be for decades to come.

17:24.468 --> 17:26.611
But I have to understand that.

17:27.032 --> 17:31.858
And what I think happens is we just collapse those down in my specific assignment right now.

17:31.938 --> 17:34.841
the job that I work at, the job that I'm in, the job that I want, right?

17:35.162 --> 17:36.844
Those all become my identity.

17:37.004 --> 17:38.185
If I haven't worked that out.

17:38.566 --> 17:41.189
And so I mean, I think that can even just be an individual exercise.

17:41.289 --> 17:43.832
If you haven't spent time doing it, just get on a piece of paper, right?

17:43.912 --> 17:46.375
Identity, calling, assignment.

17:47.115 --> 17:48.857
How would you fill out each one of those?

17:49.518 --> 17:55.645
Because I think that can help us undergird those lies of, oh man, here's my name.

17:56.286 --> 17:58.348
No, no, no, your name is child of God.

17:58.468 --> 17:59.890
Your identity is

18:00.098 --> 18:04.163
your future is secured in heaven because of Jesus.

18:04.624 --> 18:12.313
And once you know that, I think all of a sudden we can walk into the uncertainty of our moment with a much greater level of certainty for our future on identity.

18:12.333 --> 18:13.074
That's beautiful.

18:13.235 --> 18:17.740
And so, yeah, homework would be identity calling assignment, like map those out.

18:18.221 --> 18:19.122
And I also think too.

18:19.142 --> 18:20.363
In addition to the animated movie.

18:20.384 --> 18:22.446
Well, yeah, I would say maybe you're watching Prince of Egypt.

18:22.466 --> 18:23.067
I mean, you could.

18:23.387 --> 18:24.969
Yeah, you know, it might be helpful.

18:25.149 --> 18:26.491
Maybe you'll get inspired so well.

18:26.511 --> 18:26.792
Sure.

18:27.653 --> 18:28.754
But I do think like,

18:29.122 --> 18:41.277
An area that I've seen that lived out was have an opportunity to pastor at a Mountain View campus for a little while in the early 2020s, right around the time that some tech companies were imploding.

18:42.058 --> 18:58.738
I was talking to people who were on all sides of the career spectrum, some who did the lily pad thing and jumped every two years, and some who had spent 25 years at the same company, and both of them had the same exact looks in their eyes when they said, yeah, I was, I got part of a reduction in force,

18:58.818 --> 18:59.919
I'm between jobs right now.

18:59.999 --> 19:10.670
And the funny thing is like, the thing that I immediately identified as like a threat, it were were I to be in their shoes of like, well, how am I going to sustain my livelihood?

19:11.050 --> 19:18.418
And like for the most of the individuals that I talked to, as an amazing provisional blessing, they had time to figure it out.

19:19.259 --> 19:22.242
But that didn't actually like help them at all.

19:22.522 --> 19:26.546
And what 100% did help them was showing up

19:27.138 --> 19:39.034
on Friday mornings at six in the morning to eat a bagel and have a cup of coffee with a group of guys who said like this is what's going on in my life right now and I need some other men around me and I need to be prayed for because I am unmoored.

19:39.675 --> 19:44.903
I haven't taken the time to identify like the gifts and wireings in myself.

19:46.124 --> 19:48.247
I've just equated who I am with what I do.

19:49.429 --> 19:53.575
And it is like a sword through the soul separating them from who they are.

19:53.715 --> 19:56.018
And yet I am so pleased to say

19:56.322 --> 20:01.067
that all of the individuals that I connected with during that time, like God did work in them.

20:01.227 --> 20:10.796
Like I watched it happen firsthand because they were committed to identifying who they were as a child of God and within the sense of community that they so desperately needed.

20:10.816 --> 20:23.809
Yeah, I mean, I just think that there are so many potential idols that our flesh wants and that the enemy of our soul and that a broken sinful system in our world wants to deform our identity into, right?

20:23.829 --> 20:25.010
So I think our

20:25.122 --> 20:30.008
our situation, you know, our job, where we live, all that stuff, our status.

20:30.328 --> 20:35.034
I also think another one of those that I see a lot is the season that you're in.

20:35.795 --> 20:43.644
So like an easy one is when you're a student and you graduate and you just look into the world of the unknown, but you have identified as a student.

20:43.664 --> 20:48.209
And that one feels, that one still feels like a positive change, but it's scary, right?

20:48.269 --> 20:48.850
Because

20:48.962 --> 20:52.025
If you're not careful, your assignment was that you were a student.

20:52.045 --> 20:54.408
That was never your calling, it was never your identity.

20:55.089 --> 21:16.272
And then I think a big one I see for people who, their primary assignment for a long time is at home with kids or for parents in general, when kids graduate or move out, I think that, like it's so easy for that thing, especially in church culture to become your identity.

21:16.813 --> 21:18.194
You are a mom.

21:18.402 --> 21:26.812
you are a dad, but actually your primary identity is a son or a daughter, not a mom or a dad.

21:26.832 --> 21:31.418
And to be able to say, hey, before you love your son or daughter, God did.

21:32.359 --> 21:38.126
And God loves your son or daughter infinitely more than you ever can.

21:39.588 --> 21:44.594
I just think that stuff, the sooner we can do some of that substructure work, the better

21:44.770 --> 21:47.073
because if we wait, it's gonna be hard no matter what.

21:47.233 --> 21:50.337
Like I'm saying all the stuff and I'm telling you, it'll be really hard when kids move out of our house.

21:50.377 --> 21:51.699
Like I don't wanna minimize that.

21:53.361 --> 22:06.957
But I think recognizing your season, your situation, your status, all those things are competing and sort of trying to climb up from your assignment right now to your identity forever.

22:07.438 --> 22:14.066
And if you let them climb that tree, it may feel good in the moment, circumstantially,

22:14.530 --> 22:16.993
but it will be short-lived.

22:17.053 --> 22:19.537
You will be very, very frustrated if you let it stay there.

22:19.777 --> 22:20.078
Yeah.

22:20.819 --> 22:27.147
Yeah, there's, I mean, there's so much to dive into there because there's pain out there waiting for us in some way.

22:27.748 --> 22:30.011
How can we be preemptively preparing for that?

22:30.892 --> 22:33.836
So I would just say kind of a closing question for you.

22:33.877 --> 22:43.730
If someone's in the Bay Area and they're chasing the idea of arrival, optimizing life, maybe they're spiritually skeptical and they've heard nothing else

22:43.842 --> 22:49.928
that from Sunday or from a Sunday that's coming, what would you want them to wrestle with this week?

22:49.948 --> 22:51.469
What do you want people to wrestle with this week?

22:52.410 --> 23:02.419
I think the places of your life that you think God is least interested in, he is just as present, just as close as any other area.

23:02.800 --> 23:13.810
So the illusion of when I show up to church, God's like waiting for me and he has something special and unique, he wants to do there that he can't do somewhere else.

23:14.114 --> 23:30.852
It may be that God does something unique for you, but I think a lot of times when God does something unique in my mind or in my heart in a gathering of worship, it actually has a lot more to do with my attitude walking in than it even does with what's happening.

23:30.872 --> 23:33.534
I would say like, there's always two sermons getting preached.

23:34.035 --> 23:37.018
There's the one that like you, me, or another communicator are preaching.

23:37.058 --> 23:40.722
And then we've prepared and hopefully the Lord's spoken into

23:40.962 --> 23:44.006
But then there's the sermon that you are individually hearing.

23:44.647 --> 23:48.191
And I'd say sometimes in my life, those are two radically different sermons.

23:48.211 --> 23:54.640
You know, it's like, I can walk away and go, I'm not even sure what they said, but I know, I got notes about what God was leaning in.

23:55.060 --> 24:01.929
And for a lot of it, it's because it's the first time that week that the rest of the world really has just shut off for 30 minutes.

24:02.730 --> 24:08.978
And I've had a minute to process and think and, you know, have really a centering experience, but

24:09.346 --> 24:11.749
It's not because God's not interested in your commute.

24:12.189 --> 24:15.353
It's not because God's not interested in the conflict in your marriage.

24:15.373 --> 24:19.818
It's not because God's not interested in the difficult major decision you have at work.

24:19.938 --> 24:24.082
It's not because God's not interested even in the ordinary things that feel boring to you.

24:24.443 --> 24:27.807
He's just as interested and just as present in all of it.

24:28.367 --> 24:36.016
And so the peak moment you think about spiritually in your life to the thing that feels the most boring, I would just challenge you this week.

24:37.337 --> 24:38.098
Just remember,

24:38.274 --> 24:49.832
God is with you, God is near, whether you know him or not, as you do that like really silly thing, or as you do that thing, you're so glad that nobody else sees.

24:49.933 --> 24:51.735
That's a secret that's hidden.

24:52.056 --> 24:53.198
It's not hidden from him.

24:53.218 --> 24:56.443
And I don't say that to shame anyone or to guilt anyone.

24:56.843 --> 25:01.150
It's an invitation that the God of the universe who loves you, who actually made you in his image.

25:01.250 --> 25:03.474
You're an image bearer, no matter what you think about Jesus.

25:03.810 --> 25:12.299
And that should be an invitation, hopefully through this series to say, if he was willing to go to these kinds of lengths to be this close, what might I do in response?

25:12.499 --> 25:13.000
Yeah, it's great.

25:14.141 --> 25:22.550
And that I think speaks against the cultural narrative of like, just listen to this podcast or just take this medication or just do this.

25:22.590 --> 25:26.374
Like sometimes there aren't quick fixes for this, but God sees you and knows you.

25:26.814 --> 25:28.376
And I just hope that's given you hope.

25:28.796 --> 25:29.277
Yeah.

25:29.297 --> 25:30.258
And I would say,

25:30.914 --> 25:36.202
The thing that I've tried to get better about even personally, because like I'm, I live in this culture.

25:36.462 --> 25:37.564
I'm susceptible to all of this.

25:38.045 --> 25:38.966
I like technology.

25:39.307 --> 25:40.629
I'm a highly productive person.

25:40.649 --> 25:42.131
I like listen to things.

25:42.191 --> 25:46.297
I mean, it's easy for assignment to climb to calling to come to identity for me.

25:46.838 --> 25:47.920
So this is everybody thing.

25:48.861 --> 25:55.571
Um, but one of the things I've tried to do just as an adjustment is I, I listen to a lot less stuff, uh, which is a big deal for me.

25:55.611 --> 25:56.252
I'm dyslexic.

25:56.272 --> 26:00.018
So I listen to books usually before I read them, uh, helps me read them faster.

26:00.354 --> 26:02.937
or I'll like listen to podcast or whatever.

26:02.977 --> 26:08.462
And so I will quite regularly have it, you know, earbud in and I'm listening to something.

26:09.043 --> 26:27.361
And so whether that's on a drive to go pick up my daughter in Sunnyvale or, you know, a walk where I'm going somewhere downtown or whatever, I'm trying to be more present in the moment, present to what God might be doing in the lives of people around me, how I might be able to pray.

26:27.721 --> 26:28.882
And then also to just like,

26:29.090 --> 26:39.940
Actually, sort of for me, I think, now this is a little bit of expositional gymnastics here, so don't hold me biblically accountable to this.

26:40.621 --> 26:48.809
I think that if the burning bush happened today, God would yell through our noise-canceling headphones, take your AirPods out.

26:48.829 --> 26:54.474
I think the equivalent of take your sandals off would be take your AirPods out.

26:54.494 --> 26:56.376
So I'm just trying to live that out in my life.

26:56.636 --> 26:58.578
Maybe that's a word you need, I don't know.

26:58.850 --> 27:03.999
But I think, you know, at a minimum, listen to what you're listening to slower.

27:04.620 --> 27:06.544
Your brain is not a machine.

27:06.744 --> 27:09.489
It's not designed to function at the speed of computers.

27:10.351 --> 27:13.517
And I think that it's easier to hear God when there's space to listen.

27:14.158 --> 27:15.961
And we give affection to what we give attention to.

27:17.824 --> 27:18.706
That lands with me.

27:18.786 --> 27:19.327
personally.

27:19.487 --> 27:20.368
So thanks, Phil.

27:20.468 --> 27:21.269
Just just great.

27:21.610 --> 27:22.231
Yeah.

27:22.251 --> 27:25.275
In an era where our cars drive for us.

27:25.535 --> 27:27.578
So we're able to text or do anything else.

27:27.598 --> 27:31.303
And then we're listening to books or music at 2x speed for no reason.

27:31.403 --> 27:33.045
Just because we need to get it quicker.

27:33.346 --> 27:38.673
I mean, yeah, that's that is a counter narrative right there to conventional wisdom.

27:38.713 --> 27:39.474
I just like there.

27:39.554 --> 27:49.267
All of those things, there are cultural stories that we're believing about ourselves, that we're believing about the world around us, that it's like, well, if I don't do this then, well then what?

27:49.487 --> 27:52.891
What are you so convinced will happen or will not happen?

27:52.931 --> 27:59.940
And I just think we have to be careful that we don't, we're so concerned about the machines taking over.

27:59.980 --> 28:07.410
And I think we probably need to be more concerned, at least in the short term, about pretending to become machines ourselves.

28:07.906 --> 28:11.080
because it doesn't matter how hard you're pretending, it will not work.

28:11.341 --> 28:12.526
Yeah, that's great.

28:13.832 --> 28:16.242
Good reminder for me to lean in this week.

28:16.322 --> 28:18.084
Hope it's a good reminder for you as well.

28:18.164 --> 28:23.448
So if you're listening and you want to lean in more and you'd like to know more, visit menlo.church.

28:23.488 --> 28:32.436
We've got some great resources listed there for you, including a daily reading plan to help center your soul, whether it's the morning or the evening during the Lenten season.

28:33.097 --> 28:34.878
You can click on the link that's there.

28:35.058 --> 28:40.563
Or if you already have the U version app installed, just look up Menlo Church and see the IM series.

28:40.903 --> 28:46.308
If you have prayer or any questions that you want to throw our way, you can text our team 650.

28:46.288 --> 28:46.811
600 0402.

28:46.851 --> 28:49.969
Thanks for joining us.

28:50.492 --> 28:50.693
Peace.

28:50.975 --> 28:51.538
See you everybody.

